A bit sad today, as there wasn't much softening. If you have very tight hips. this practice is not available. You can use props to help, which are great, but there is no time to  actually use them. If you are a beginner on this journey, you could become discouraged. There are so many pointers and adjustments in these practices for other  things that could be problematic, and so many cues that if they are  difficult, then just  to return to sukasana, but it doesn't often happen in reverse..Maybe a suggestion at beginning of practice,to have things ready to asist, and then some time to use them, could make this, and any hip opening practice more inclusive.

I have done the 30 day challenge then moved on to the True challenge. Love it completely. I have a question though and feel quite lost at the moment. I had a full posterior hip replacement 5 years ago, at an early age due to hip dysplasia. I have been doing yoga every day for 2 months and got to this, Day 11 of true and about 1/2 way through in a deep lunge with my back knee on the ground, I dislocated the artificial hip and after a few loud terrible words, it popped right back in. I have been xrayed and all is good, nothing wrong or out of place. Here is my lost part..I am afraid to do yoga now. I don't even know where to start to go back or how to get past the hurdle in my mind. Do you have any suggestions of sequences to do or how to get my head back? Many thanks, I adore you Adriene and all you have brought to my life in yoga.

Today I finished my 71st day of yoga with Adriene!  Its probably taken between 90 and 100 days to do it but thats okay, i do it every day im able.  My heels still dont touch in DD, i cant fly in crow (i can barely do the squats!), I m trying to learn how to get into a headstand but dont even come close to getting both feet off the ground, and I still hate anything close to guided meditation with a passion... BUT Im still showing up regularly, im learning to work within my body's limitations, and I try something to push myself just a little further every day.  I call that a success!  Thanks, Adrienne!   Now to shoot for that 100th yoga practice!

I find myself not even thinking about a pose per se, but instead really catering to relaxing and breathing with my movements. ‚ÄúCatching a wave‚Äù has been my new theme as I move in and out of the asanas.
